Patch Set 19: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Lai, I'm not so much against the "lfs getsom" helper for now, until we have proper statx() support for this, since some users/tools may want to get this information outside of test scripts, and decoding the hex xattr format is not pleasant, though it could be done more easily than you suggest, and entirely in the shell:

    som=$(getfattr -d -m trusted.som -e hex /path/to/file}
    som=${som##*=0x} # cut off everything before =0x
    flags=0x${som:0:2}
    size=0x${som:8:8}
    blocks=0x${som:16:8}

but these would also need to be swabbed (which is hard in the shell, and it is just messy in general).

What would also be useful (in a separate patch) is to return the LSOM size/blocks in the stat info as part of ioctl(IOC_MDC_GETFILEINFO) so that "lfs find" can use it (if non-zero, ignore it otherwise).  For many purposes, the LSOM size would be enough (i.e. is this file larger than 1GB), but if the file timestamp is very recent (< 10 minutes) or the size is very close to the threshold (within 10%?), then it may still make sense to do a stat.

For now, the only thing making it -1 IMHO is the lack of swabbing for big-endian clients.

